00:49:37,200 --> 00:49:39,920
where there's guys kind of circling their group.

666
00:49:40,620 --> 00:49:42,800
Some of these guys might have ulterior motives.

667
00:49:42,940 --> 00:49:45,200
It's very stressful at times.

668
00:49:45,660 --> 00:49:48,360
Sort of a less comedic Spring Breakers in that

669
00:49:48,360 --> 00:49:53,640
it just puts you in the mindset of a young hot girl on vacation

670
00:49:55,700 --> 00:49:58,560
who once she starts drinking and having fun at night

671
00:49:58,560 --> 00:49:59,840
is in a great deal of danger.

672
00:50:00,360 --> 00:50:03,360
So the movie becomes pretty dark and somber,

673
00:50:03,760 --> 00:50:04,980
but an important movie.

674
00:50:04,980 --> 00:50:08,600
I dug it. I liked it. Check it out.

675
00:50:10,260 --> 00:50:13,780
I watched, speaking of Keith Robinson,

676
00:50:14,020 --> 00:50:18,020
Keith Robinson's new Netflix special, Different Strokes.

677
00:50:18,780 --> 00:50:21,880
Keith is one of my closest friends in comedy

678
00:50:21,880 --> 00:50:24,880
and has been a bit of a mentor for me over the years.

679
00:50:25,420 --> 00:50:26,660
He had two strokes.

680
00:50:27,840 --> 00:50:31,660
The second one rendered the right side of his body.

681
00:50:31,660 --> 00:50:35,860
He can't use his right arm and he walks with a cane now.

682
00:50:36,480 --> 00:50:37,880
But he's still out there doing comedy

683
00:50:37,880 --> 00:50:40,640
and he's still out there doing what I would say is the best comedy

684
00:50:40,640 --> 00:50:42,060
he's arguably ever done.

685
00:50:43,240 --> 00:50:47,760
His special, Different Strokes covers exactly that, his two strokes.

686
00:50:48,240 --> 00:50:50,020
It is hilarious.

687
00:50:51,540 --> 00:50:53,780
It's never at any point heartbreaking.

688
00:50:54,100 --> 00:50:55,920
It's never at any point sad.

689
00:50:56,700 --> 00:50:59,220
It's truly funny all the way through

690
00:50:59,780 --> 00:51:02,800
because he leans into the fact that he's kind of an asshole.

691
00:51:03,960 --> 00:51:05,280
My favorite joke in the whole thing

692
00:51:05,280 --> 00:51:07,660
is he's talking about getting mad at God

693
00:51:07,660 --> 00:51:10,440
and going, what did I do to deserve this?

694
00:51:10,780 --> 00:51:11,700
Oh, yeah.

695
00:51:15,860 --> 00:51:17,600
So it's a great special.

696
00:51:17,800 --> 00:51:19,260
Amy Schumer produced it.

697
00:51:20,220 --> 00:51:22,020
It's awesome. It's just a great special.

698
00:51:22,140 --> 00:51:23,000
It's really funny.

699
00:51:25,300 --> 00:51:28,040
And the one part I got a little teary

700
00:51:28,740 --> 00:51:31,120
was when I watched him walk out on stage

701
00:51:31,120 --> 00:51:32,200
and get a standing ovation.

702
00:51:32,440 --> 00:51:34,560
And then at the end, there's a shot of his face

703
00:51:34,560 --> 00:51:36,340
and you can see how much this means to him.

704
00:51:36,520 --> 00:51:38,200
You can see he's like, I did this.

705
00:51:38,580 --> 00:51:42,840
And the guy's spirit as a person is incredible.

706
00:51:43,160 --> 00:51:45,620
You know, he has mobility issues, obviously.

707
00:51:46,160 --> 00:51:49,920
And to watch him show up at the clubs every night in New York,

708
00:51:50,720 --> 00:51:53,500
walk, drive his own car,

709
00:51:53,500 --> 00:52:00,560
park, walk 30 minutes in what should take seven or 10

710
00:52:00,560 --> 00:52:04,780
because he moves so slowly by himself with a cane,

711
00:52:05,660 --> 00:52:07,560
pushing through all of that,

712
00:52:08,200 --> 00:52:11,440
getting up on stage every night, doing this.

713
00:52:11,740 --> 00:52:13,980
It's truly, truly incredible.

714
00:52:14,220 --> 00:52:16,520
And it was really nice to see the final product.

715
00:52:16,600 --> 00:52:17,720
And I'm very proud of Keith.

716
00:52:18,400 --> 00:52:20,280
And it's a really funny special.

717
00:52:20,600 --> 00:52:21,840
So check it out.

718
00:52:22,560 --> 00:52:23,860
In my queue.

719
00:52:24,140 --> 00:52:25,840
I can't wait to see it.

720
00:52:28,080 --> 00:52:30,040
I rewatched, though I hadn't seen it

721
00:52:30,040 --> 00:52:32,020
since I was a little tiny kid.

722
00:52:32,080 --> 00:52:35,600
Like I remember watching it pre -10, I think, on television.

723
00:52:36,260 --> 00:52:38,140
The Sugarland Express.

724
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:41,400
That is Steven Spielberg's second movie,

725
00:52:41,660 --> 00:52:43,040
his follow -up to Duel.

726
00:52:45,400 --> 00:52:46,900
And it's good.

727
00:52:46,980 --> 00:52:47,920
It's not great.

728
00:52:48,860 --> 00:52:50,800
Spielberg immediately, I love Duel.

729
00:52:50,800 --> 00:52:52,040
I think Duel's fucking awesome.

730
00:52:52,080 --> 00:52:53,900
But immediately after these early movies,

731
00:52:53,900 --> 00:52:55,760
he'd snapped into like making nothing

732
00:52:55,760 --> 00:52:57,420
but masterpieces for a while.

733
00:52:58,680 --> 00:53:00,600
So he's kind of finding his way.

734
00:53:00,720 --> 00:53:03,020
The Sugarland Express, you don't watch it

735
00:53:03,020 --> 00:53:04,620
in the way you watch Duel,

736
00:53:04,620 --> 00:53:06,740
where you're like, this guy is a master

737
00:53:06,740 --> 00:53:08,100
who's going to go the distance.

738
00:53:08,500 --> 00:53:11,980
This is much more, it has kind of a TV movie feel to it.

739
00:53:12,680 --> 00:53:16,280
It's Goldie Hawn, a very, very young Goldie Hawn,

740
00:53:16,340 --> 00:53:19,400
and her husband are having their child taken away

741
00:53:19,400 --> 00:53:20,660
by the state of Texas.

742
00:53:21,380 --> 00:53:23,200
And they decide they're going to do whatever

743
00:53:23,200 --> 00:53:24,620
it takes to get him back.

744
00:53:24,660 --> 00:53:27,100
They kidnap a highway patrolman,

745
00:53:27,100 --> 00:53:29,680
and there's a big pursuit, basically.

746
00:53:30,560 --> 00:53:34,280
The Blues Brothers famously shouts out Steven Spielberg.

747
00:53:34,340 --> 00:53:36,580
He's working in the office at the end of the movie

748
00:53:36,580 --> 00:53:39,280
when they finally get to the office

749
00:53:39,280 --> 00:53:41,940
where they're supposed to pay the orphanage's bill.

750
00:53:42,380 --> 00:53:43,840
And it's Steven Spielberg.

751
00:53:44,200 --> 00:53:46,740
And you realize in that moment that I think

752
00:53:46,740 --> 00:53:48,980
John Landis was probably heavily influenced

753
00:53:48,980 --> 00:53:51,100
by early Spielberg because this movie

754
00:53:51,100 --> 00:53:53,880
feels a lot like the less comedic Blues Brothers.

755
00:53:54,400 --> 00:53:59,760
The back half of the movie is 70s style cars

756
00:53:59,760 --> 00:54:02,000
just piling up on each other,

757
00:54:02,060 --> 00:54:04,240
crashing, flying over embankments.

758
00:54:06,060 --> 00:54:06,740
It's cool.

759
00:54:07,400 --> 00:54:09,820
It's a small character study

760
00:54:09,820 --> 00:54:12,180
that turns into a giant car chase movie.

761
00:54:13,660 --> 00:54:16,160
Not classic Spielberg, but if you've never seen it,

762
00:54:16,160 --> 00:54:18,520
it's a fun movie, and Goldie Hawn is great in it.

763
00:54:18,800 --> 00:54:19,040
Joe?

764
00:54:20,640 --> 00:54:24,820
I have one more, again, on topic.

765
00:54:25,220 --> 00:54:28,300
The Acolyte, the new Star Wars show on Disney+.

766
00:54:28,720 --> 00:54:29,500
I'm curious about it.

767
00:54:31,640 --> 00:54:33,620
Well, look, I'm not...

768
00:54:33,620 --> 00:54:34,780
You know, you were saying earlier,

769
00:54:34,940 --> 00:54:36,820
if you express certain things,

770
00:54:37,140 --> 00:54:40,100
you kind of inadvertently get in league

771
00:54:40,100 --> 00:54:41,980
with people you don't want to be in league with.

772
00:54:42,320 --> 00:54:42,660
Yeah.

773
00:54:42,660 --> 00:54:46,120
I certainly don't want to be in league with...

774
00:54:46,120 --> 00:54:49,020
Not that I disagree with all of their points,

775
00:54:49,080 --> 00:54:51,520
but I don't want to be in league with these YouTubers

776
00:54:51,520 --> 00:54:54,460
that are constantly... that have made their lives

777
00:54:54,460 --> 00:54:56,920
about complaining about Kathleen Kennedy

778
00:54:56,920 --> 00:54:58,600
and Star Wars being too woke.

779
00:55:01,760 --> 00:55:03,700
The Acolyte is not a good show.

780
00:55:03,800 --> 00:55:06,580
It's just not. It looks beautiful.

781
00:55:07,300 --> 00:55:11,460
It's the most high -quality Star Wars product

782
00:55:11,460 --> 00:55:13,100
that I've seen hit the television,

783
00:55:15,180 --> 00:55:18,260
and it had, I think, double the budget of Obi -Wan,

784
00:55:18,440 --> 00:55:20,000
which is a weird thing to do.

785
00:55:20,060 --> 00:55:23,400
It's weird to go, we're going to do a limited series

786
00:55:23,400 --> 00:55:25,220
that features Ewan McGregor,

787
00:55:25,540 --> 00:55:29,560
and it's going to be about one of the biggest characters

788
00:55:29,560 --> 00:55:31,600
in the history of this franchise,

789
00:55:32,280 --> 00:55:35,940
and it's going to fill in the gaps between the prequels

790
00:55:36,400 --> 00:55:37,660
and the original trilogy,

791
00:55:38,260 --> 00:55:39,740
and Darth Vader's going to come back.

792
00:55:39,740 --> 00:55:43,480
It's weird to give that half the budget of the Acolyte,

793
00:55:44,360 --> 00:55:46,640
which has none of that stuff in it,

794
00:55:47,140 --> 00:55:48,940
but you can see it on the screen.

795
00:55:49,080 --> 00:55:50,540
It looks great.

796
00:55:51,420 --> 00:55:53,500
And I think the story is cool.

797
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,940
I'm not... Everybody's mad about it's...

798
00:55:56,940 --> 00:55:59,360
It's betraying canon and all this stuff.

799
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:01,980
I don't know. I thought the story was cool.

800
00:56:02,080 --> 00:56:02,980
I thought it was interesting.

801
00:56:03,500 --> 00:56:06,040
I just think the execution of everything is bad.

802
00:56:06,220 --> 00:56:07,620
The acting is bad.

803
00:56:08,560 --> 00:56:11,860
The writing is okay.

804
00:56:14,080 --> 00:56:16,720
I was going to maybe watch this one

805
00:56:16,720 --> 00:56:20,440
because I love the writer, Leslie Hedlund.

806
00:56:21,140 --> 00:56:22,960
So I'm bummed to hear it's not great,

807
00:56:23,020 --> 00:56:24,520
because she did Russian Doll,

808
00:56:24,560 --> 00:56:26,180
which I think is kind of a brilliant show,

809
00:56:26,360 --> 00:56:27,340
first season anyway,

810
00:56:29,020 --> 00:56:30,940
Sleeping with Other People with Sudeikis,

811
00:56:30,980 --> 00:56:32,560
which I thought was a great rom -com,

812
00:56:32,660 --> 00:56:34,760
one of the really good modern rom -coms.

813
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:36,760
Bachelorette with Kirsten Dunst, which I loved.

814
00:56:36,760 --> 00:56:40,660
But I also was confused as to why she was taking this,

815
00:56:40,900 --> 00:56:43,660
because her MO is usually writing very smart,

816
00:56:44,900 --> 00:56:47,960
very R -rated dialogue, usually for women.

817
00:56:48,360 --> 00:56:48,760
So I was...

818
00:56:49,300 --> 00:56:51,320
She's not necessarily the name I would think of,

819
00:56:51,380 --> 00:56:52,220
but she's a great writer.

820
00:56:52,880 --> 00:56:55,760
Well, it's this thing that...

821
00:56:56,600 --> 00:56:58,320
You know, usually what happens

822
00:56:59,200 --> 00:57:01,240
with these big franchises,

823
00:57:01,300 --> 00:57:02,780
and we've talked about it,

824
00:57:02,980 --> 00:57:05,900
is they go find some up -and -coming,

825
00:57:06,400 --> 00:57:08,160
amazing indie film director,

826
00:57:08,640 --> 00:57:09,020
and they go,

827
00:57:09,160 --> 00:57:11,900
this guy is somebody we can handcuff,

828
00:57:12,120 --> 00:57:14,340
versus a Joe Dante or somebody

829
00:57:14,340 --> 00:57:15,500
who's going to come in and tell us

830
00:57:15,500 --> 00:57:17,360
what we need to do to make the movie good.

831
00:57:17,740 --> 00:57:20,380
And we'll puppeteer him, and he'll do what we say,

832
00:57:20,420 --> 00:57:22,000
or she'll do what we say, and that'll be it.

833
00:57:23,200 --> 00:57:24,360
Lucasfilm is doing the opposite.

834
00:57:24,600 --> 00:57:26,180
They're going to get in these young...

835
00:57:26,180 --> 00:57:29,920
Not young people, but these lesser -known mainstream people,

836
00:57:30,280 --> 00:57:32,220
and they're going, do your thing.

837
00:57:32,720 --> 00:57:34,240
And it's not working.

838
00:57:34,240 --> 00:57:36,280
They did it with Rian Johnson.

839
00:57:36,500 --> 00:57:38,800
It's not working. It's just not working.

840
00:57:38,960 --> 00:57:40,580
Like, you have to guide these people,

841
00:57:42,360 --> 00:57:43,560
and she's...

842
00:57:43,560 --> 00:57:45,280
The writing's not terrible.

843
00:57:45,500 --> 00:57:46,640
It's not terrible.

844
00:57:46,760 --> 00:57:48,200
The dialogue is not great.

845
00:57:48,300 --> 00:57:49,980
It's passable. It's good enough.

846
00:57:50,560 --> 00:57:52,700
Star Wars has never had amazing dialogue.

847
00:57:53,440 --> 00:57:56,740
It's the acting, and the vibe of the show,

848
00:57:57,480 --> 00:58:01,580
it feels very, like, Matrix -y or something.

849
00:58:01,640 --> 00:58:02,660
It's just off.

850
00:58:02,660 --> 00:58:05,580
And it's a shame, because it could be cool.

851
00:58:06,060 --> 00:58:08,940
People are bitching that it's too woke and all that stuff.

852
00:58:09,740 --> 00:58:10,840
I got to be honest with you.

853
00:58:10,920 --> 00:58:13,460
I thought it was going to be way more heavy -handed

854
00:58:13,460 --> 00:58:15,200
with some kind of agenda or whatever.

855
00:58:15,260 --> 00:58:17,880
It's not. It's just not great.

856
00:58:19,540 --> 00:58:21,280
But everybody's targeting it,

857
00:58:21,500 --> 00:58:23,900
and they're going to try to make an example out of it.

858
00:58:23,940 --> 00:58:25,880
And I think that's stupid.

859
00:58:27,400 --> 00:58:30,660
But, you know, it's...

860
00:58:31,100 --> 00:58:33,620
I feel like it could have been good. I really do.

861
00:58:34,500 --> 00:58:36,220
Whereas Obi -Wan, by the end of it,

862
00:58:36,220 --> 00:58:39,920
I was fucking furious at the decisions they were making.

863
00:58:40,160 --> 00:58:41,660
I don't feel like that with this.

864
00:58:41,800 --> 00:58:43,700
I just feel like it's just not...

865
00:58:43,700 --> 00:58:45,300
It's just not hitting the mark.

866
00:58:45,800 --> 00:58:47,760
There's some really cool concepts, though.

867
00:58:47,980 --> 00:58:52,660
And actually, I think she does have a great respect,

868
00:58:53,720 --> 00:58:56,420
despite some of the things she has said.

869
00:58:58,120 --> 00:59:00,200
I think a lot of what she's said publicly

870
00:59:00,200 --> 00:59:03,780
about Star Wars has been a little misconstrued and whatever.

871
00:59:04,220 --> 00:59:08,200
But I do think she has quite a respect for the mythology of it,

872
00:59:08,200 --> 00:59:10,520
and I think she has quite a respect for what it is.

873
00:59:11,120 --> 00:59:13,500
I just wish this was being carried out better.

874
00:59:13,680 --> 00:59:15,480
And I think it's not being carried out better

875
00:59:15,480 --> 00:59:18,000
because they don't have somebody in that company

876
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:20,520
that's saying, here's how you do this.

877
00:59:20,900 --> 00:59:22,560
Because I don't think that person exists there.

878
00:59:23,040 --> 00:59:24,260
I used to think it was Dave Filoni.

879
00:59:24,560 --> 00:59:25,660
I love Dave Filoni.

880
00:59:25,960 --> 00:59:27,620
I'm starting to lose a bit of faith in him,

881
00:59:27,620 --> 00:59:29,560
but we'll see what happens.

882
00:59:32,480 --> 00:59:34,240
Let's get to that movie at hand.

883
00:59:34,420 --> 00:59:38,780
This is a title that I have not been able to remember

884
00:59:38,780 --> 00:59:40,460
any time I've tried to say it.

885
00:59:40,580 --> 00:59:42,800
It's too many words or too much something,

886
00:59:43,440 --> 00:59:49,000
but it is called In a Violent Nature.

887
00:59:49,400 --> 00:59:49,780
Yes.

888
00:59:50,420 --> 00:59:51,720
I think that's why I don't remember it.

889
00:59:51,720 --> 00:59:53,060
It's not even proper grammar.

890
00:59:53,680 --> 00:59:54,980
All the violent nature.

891
00:59:55,560 --> 00:59:58,280
I just realized, in a violent nature,

892
00:59:58,280 --> 01:00:00,760
because they're in the woods, nature.

893
01:00:01,640 --> 01:00:03,580
I never put that together until right now,

894
01:00:03,780 --> 01:00:06,400
the play on words, because it doesn't work, really.

895
01:00:06,760 --> 01:00:08,140
I think it's a good title.

896
01:00:09,600 --> 01:00:10,020
Yeah.

897
01:00:10,280 --> 01:00:10,820
I don't know.

898
01:00:11,400 --> 01:00:12,680
Of a violent nature.

899
01:00:13,660 --> 01:00:14,900
Having a violent nature.

900
01:00:15,060 --> 01:00:17,400
In a violent nature, it doesn't work for me.

901
01:00:19,360 --> 01:00:21,400
Yeah, the movie, look,

902
01:00:22,200 --> 01:00:27,740
there's a real bare bones of a plot to this thing.

903
01:00:29,300 --> 01:00:31,900
The basic gist of the movie, let's face it,

904
01:00:31,900 --> 01:00:35,460
